    "section": "Guides",
    "order": 10,
    "body": "\n# Manage your organization\n\nAn **organization** decides who can reach your projects. You always have a\n**personal** org (just you); create a **team** org to work with others.\n\n## Roles\n\n| Role | Can do |\n|---|---|\n| **Owner** | Everything, including renaming/deleting the org and managing owners. |\n| **Admin** | Manage members and every project in the org. |\n| **Member** | Belongs to the org; project access is granted per project. |\n\nOrg owners and admins automatically administer every project in the org. Plain\nmembers only see projects they're explicitly added to.\n\n## Create a team organization\n\n1. Open **Settings → Organizations** and choose **Create organization**.\n2. Give it a name and a short URL slug (lowercase letters, digits, hyphens).\n3. You become its owner. Switch between orgs any time with the org switcher in\n   the sidebar.\n\n## Invite people\n\n1. In **Settings → Organizations**, open your team org's **Members**.\n2. Enter a teammate's email and pick a role.\n   - If they already have a Forge account, they're added immediately.\n   - If not, they receive an email invitation to join with that role.\n3. Change a member's role or remove them from the same list. Pending email\n   invitations can be revoked there too.\n\n## Move a project between orgs\n\nOpen **Project → Settings → Advanced → Move to organization** and pick the\ndestination. You must be an owner/admin of **both** the current and the\ndestination org. The project's own members are kept.\n\n## Notes\n\n- An org must always keep at least one owner.\n- A personal org can't be renamed, deleted, or given extra members.\n- Deleting a team org requires moving or deleting its projects first.\n"
